<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18500610-1208">
               <interp inst="t18500610-1208" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18500610"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18500610-1208" type="date" value="18500610"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18500610-1208-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1208-18500610 t18500610-1208-offence-1 t18500610-1208-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1208. <persName id="def1-1208-18500610" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1208-18500610" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1208-18500610" type="age" value="22"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1208-18500610" type="surname" value="M'NAIR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1208-18500610" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES M'NAIR</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18500610-1208-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18500610-1208-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18500610-1208-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="burglary"></interp>, stealing 25 cigars and 4 oz. weight of tobacco, value 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 8 half-crowns, 60 pence, and 120 halfpence; the property of <persName id="t18500610-name-918" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-918" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-918" type="surname" value="HIPPISLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-918" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18500610-1208-offence-1 t18500610-name-918"></join>John Hippisley</persName>, in his dwelling-house, and afterwards burglariously breaking out of the said dwelling-house.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BIRNIE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-919" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-919" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-919" type="surname" value="RATLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-919" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT RATLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I was formerly in the V. division of police. About three o'clock in the morning of 18th April, I was on duty in Southampton-street, Lambeth, and heard some one walking in the yard at the back of the Southampton Arms public-house—I pulled myself up to the top of a side gate, looked over, and saw the prisoner coming down the stone-steps leading from the house into the yard—I could see him plainly; I have no doubt about him—I have known him for years, he is the son of the person who used to keep the house—I got down from the gate and went back for three or four yards, and he came and put his hands on the top of the gate, and his feet on the top of the bar, and got up—I asked what he did there—he said he was waiting for some Norman cows that were coming up by the railroad—I told him he had no business there, and he instantly went back—I went and spoke to Howard, another constable, and in two or three minutes I went in by ano<lb></lb>ther gate, leaving Howard there—I found the door at the top of the steps where I had seen the prisoner, wide open—I went in and called up the land<lb></lb>lord, and we searched the place all over, but could not find the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> You say you saw me quite plain? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, I was about three yards from you—I have known you three or four years, and am certain you are the man—I should know you from a thousand—I did not see you that night at the corner of Nine-Elms-lane, nor did you then tell me about the cows.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-920" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-920" type="surname" value="HIPPISLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-920" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HIPPISLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep the Southampton Arms, Lambeth; I have had the house twelve months; I succeeded the prisoner's father when he left the house. On 18th April, about three o'clock in the morning, I was called up by the policeman, and found the front and back-doors open—(I had gone to bed about half-past eleven overnight, and left all the doors bolted)—I missed two papers containing copper money, eight half-crowns, and some cigars and tobacco—I had left them in a drawer—I know the prisoner quite well—I saw him in our house about seven o'clock the previous evening, the 17th—I have here a paper similar to that in which the tobacco I lost was wrapped.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-921" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-921" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-921" type="surname" value="PEGRAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-921" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>DAVID PEGRAM</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, L</hi> 161). On the night of 18th April the prisoner was brought to the station on a stretcher, from the effects of swal<lb></lb>lowing a screw of tobacco—he was brought in for dead, insensible—I sent for a medical man, who recovered him, and he was taken home—after he was gone, in consequence of information, I went after him, and found him at 55, Mount-street, Westminster-road, a night-house—I told him I had received information from the B division station that he was wanted, for a robbery at the Southampton Arms—he made use of some words to his companion, which I could not understand, owing to the noise in the house—I searched the pri<lb></lb>soner, and found on him two half-crowns, two sixpences, 5 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in copper, two screws of tobacco, and one paper which had had tobacco in—I have also produced a paper which was given me by Mr. Hippisley, and three others which I got as samples from the prosecutor's house.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185006100163"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-922" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-922" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-922" type="surname" value="HIPPISLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-922" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HIPPISLEY</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This is the paper I gave the policeman—it was cut from a memorandum-book, and the papers left behind in the drawer correspond in the figures and writing with those found on the prisoner—I do not make up the screws myself; we buy them ready made up—I sold some of these the same morning—I had in two pounds of them the same evening, at seven o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-923" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-923" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-923" type="surname" value="CROUCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-923" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CROUCH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to a gentleman, and live at 9, Bond-street, Vauxhall. On Wednesday, 17th April, I was at the bar of the Southampton Arms, between eleven and twelve o'clock, and saw the prisoner come in—I knew him before—I left as near twelve o'clock as possible, and I believe I left him there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-924" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-924" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-924" type="surname" value="SKUDDER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-924" type="given" value="JAKES"></interp>JAKES SKUDDER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am potman to Mr. Hippisley. On the night of 17th April I shut up the shutters, about twenty-five minutes to twelve o'clock—there was then only one person in the room, and that was a porter—I saw the prisoner sitting outside the front-door on a seat—I am sure it was him—I spoke to him—I had seen him in the tap-room, between eleven and twelve—I bolted the back-door before I went to bed, about five minutes past twe e—my mistress and the servant were the last persons up—they are not here—a gentleman who was in the tap-room that night said that he expected some Alderney cows up next morning, and the prisoner was there at the time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-925" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-925" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-925" type="surname" value="SIMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-925" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN SIMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am single, and live at 2, Vale-place, Duke-street, West<lb></lb>minster-road. On the morning of 18th April, I met the prisoner at Hart's public-house, in Mount-street—we had something to drink, and he went home with me—he gave me half-a-crown and sixpence, and he also gave me a cigar or a cheroot—he had given one to some females at the public-house—he paid 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 11 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for his breakfast—he had about half-a-dozen cigars in his hand—I saw no papers of tobacco.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-926" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-926" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-926" type="surname" value="HART"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-926" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY HART</persName>
                  </hi>. I am barman to my father, who keeps the New Crown and Cushion, in Westminster-road. On 18th April, between four and five in the morning, the prisoner came and had half-a-pint of gin, which I believe he paid for in silver—he then asked if I would oblige him by giving him five shillings for a five shilling packet of halfpence, but I said I did not want them—he then broke open a package of halfpence, and spent three or four shillings' worth treating a lot of persons at the bar, and he smoked some cheroots or cigars which he took out of his pocket—he left the house a little after six with Simpson—I did not hear of his swallowing any tobacco.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I know nothing of it.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18500610-1208-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18500610-1208-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18500610-1208-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="lesserOffence"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi> 
                     <hi rend="italic">of Stealing in the dwelling-house.</hi> Aged 22.—<hi rend="italic">Recommended to mercy</hi>
                  </rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">by the Jury.—
<rs id="t18500610-1208-punishment-164" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-1208-punishment-164" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
